"Yvon-Lewis S.A., Butler J.H.","Effect of oceanic uptake on atmospheric lifetimes of selected trace gases",2002,"Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres","107","20",,"XXLVII","XXLVIII",,,10.1029/2001JD001267,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-36448932817&partnerID=40&md5=1914707eeecbb6751d73b68c47e1103a","Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Miami, FL, United States; Climate Monitoring and Diagnostics Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Boulder, CO, United States; Climate Monitoring and Diagnostics Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 325 Broadway, Boulder, CO 80303, United States; Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 4301 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149-1026, United States","Yvon-Lewis, S.A., Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Miami, FL, United States, Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 4301 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149-1026, United States; Butler, J.H., Climate Monitoring and Diagnostics Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Boulder, CO, United States, Climate Monitoring and Diagnostics Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 325 Broadway, Boulder, CO 80303, United States","We have calculated from a 2° × 2° grid of oceanic properties the contribution of oceanic loss to the overall lifetimes of a number of anthropogenic and naturally produced trace gases involved in global warming and stratospheric ozone depletion. The model, originally developed for atmospheric methyl bromide, can be used for any well-mixed trace gas where the seawater degradation rate constants and solubilities are known. Of the gases tested, it is clear that known oceanic chemical degradation processes alone are not significant sinks for most HFCs and HCFCs. Chemical degradation in the oceans is a substantial sink for COS (28%) and COCl2 (8%) and a minor sink for CH3C1 (&lt;2%) and CH3I (2.5%), and it should be considered when determining atmospheric lifetimes and sink strengths for these gases. Biological degradation processes are likely to increase the oceanic uptake rates of many gases.","0312 Atmospheric Composition and Structure: Air/sea constituent fluxes (3339,4504); 0322 Atmospheric Composition and Structure: Constituent sources and sinks; 0399 Atmospheric Composition and Structure: General or miscellaneous; Lifetime; Oceanic uptake",,,,,,,"Ashworth, R.A., Howe, G.B., Mulins, M.E., Rogers, T.N., Air-water partitioning coefficients of organics in dilute aqueous solutions (1988) J. Hazard. Mater., 18, pp. 25-36; Bridgeman, C.H., Pyle, J.A., Shallcross, D.E., A three-dimensional model calculation of the ozone depletion potential of 1-bromopropane (1C3H7Br) (2000) J. Geophys. Res., 105, pp. 26,493-26,502; Butler, J.H., The potential role of the ocean in regulating atmospheric CH3Br (1994) Geophys. Res. Lett., 21, pp. 185-188; Butler, J.H., Rodriguez, J.M., Methyl bromide in the atmosphere (1996) The Methyl Bromide Issue, pp. 27-90. , edited by C. Bell, N. Price, and B. Chakrabarti, John Wiley, New York; Butler, J.H., Elkins, J.W., Thompson, T.M., Hall, B.D., Swanson, T.H., Koropalov, V., Oceanic consumption of CH3CCl3: Implications for tropospheric OH (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 22,347-22,355; Butler, J.H., Elkins, J.W., Thompson, T.M., Hall, B.D., Lobert, J.M., Swanson, T.H., Koropalov, V., (1993) A Significant Oceanic Sink For Atmospheric CCl4, , paper presented Third Scientific Meetina, Oceanogr. Soc., Seattle, Wash., 13-16 April; Butler, J.H., Elkins, J.W., Lobert, J.M., Montzka, S.A., Koropolov, V., Significant global loss of atmospheric CCl4 to the ocean (1997) Eos Trans. AGU, 78 (46 FALL MEET. SUPPL.), pp. F105; Castro, C.E., Biodehalogenation: T